summary: This is an email chain from November 18, 2021, regarding a query from Telegraph journalist Josie Ensor to the U.S. Attorney's Office for the Southern District of New York (USANYS) about an unredacted witness name in the Ghislaine Maxwell case. The prosecutor urgently requests the journalist not to publish the name while they verify the information.

persons.name: Josie Ensor
persons.context: A correspondent for the British Telegraph newspaper who emails the U.S. Attorney's Office to inquire about reporting on an unredacted witness name in the Ghislaine Maxwell case filing.

persons.name: Ghislaine Maxwell
persons.context: The subject of the criminal case (United States vs. Maxwell) referenced in the email. The query concerns a filing in her trial.

events.title: Journalist inquiry about unredacted witness name
events.description: Journalist Josie Ensor contacts the U.S. Attorney's Office to ask if they can report on a witness name that was left unredacted in a public filing (Document #453) in the Ghislaine Maxwell case.

keyFacts: A filing in the United States vs. Maxwell case (Document #453) contained an unredacted name of a government-proposed witness.
The U.S. Attorney's Office was urgently notified by a journalist and requested the name not be published while they verified the information.
The judge in the Maxwell case had allowed witnesses and victims to remain anonymous through the trial if they chose.
The communication highlights the sensitivity and procedural handling of witness identities in the high-profile case.
